.SH NAME
describe-bindings \- Show current command/key binding
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
\fBdescribe-bindings\fR \*(C0
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B describe-bindings
pops up a  window with a list of  all the named commands, and the
keys currently bound to them. Each entry is formatted as:
.IP
.B keyCode
\fC\.\.\.\.\.\.\.\.\.\.\.\fR
.B command
.LP
.B describe-bindings
is buffer  context  sensitive and shows the bindings for the currently  active
buffer  (i.e. the buffer  that is active  when the  command is  invoked).  The
resultant command list is divided into three sections as follows:
.IP "\fBBuffer Bindings\fR"
The bindings for the active buffer when  \fBdescribe-bindings\fR  was invoked.
These are the buffer bindings set by
.Ht buffer-bind-key 2 .
.IP "\fBMl Bindings\fR"
The message line bindings as set by
.Ht ml-bind-key 2 .
.IP "\fBGlobal Bindings\fR"
Global binding of keys as set by
.Ht global-bind-key 2 .
